title:
The Abundance and Properties of Barred Galaxies out to $z \sim$ 4 Using
  $\textit{JWST}$ CEERS Data

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We present the first estimate of the observed fraction and properties of bars out to $z \sim 4$ using $J W S T$ CEERS NIRCam images. We analyze 1770 galaxies with $M_{*}>10^{10} M_{\odot}$ at $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$ and identify barred galaxies from 839 moderately inclined disk galaxies via ellipse fits and visual classification of both F200W and F444W images. Our results apply mainly to bars with projected semi-major axis $a_{\text {bar }}$ $>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ ( $\sim 2 \times \mathrm{PSF}$ in F200W images) that can be robustly traced by ellipse fits. For such bars, the observed bar fraction at $z \sim 2-4$ is low ( $\lesssim 10 \%$ ), and they appear to be emerging at least as early as $z \sim 4$. Our observed bar fraction is consistent with the bar fraction predicted by TNG50 simulations for large bars with $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ at $z \sim 0.5-4$ and with the bar fraction from Auriga simulations out to $z \sim 1.5$. However, TNG50 simulations predict a large population of smaller bars that our data cannot robustly detect. If such bars exist, the true bar fraction at $z \sim 2-4$ may be significantly higher than our results. At $z \geq 1.5$, many barred galaxies show nearby neighbors, suggesting bars may be tidally triggered. From $z \sim 4-0.5$, the observed bar fraction, average projected bar length, and projected bar strength rise. Our results highlight the early emergence and evolution of barred galaxies and the rising importance of bar-driven secular evolution from $z \sim 4$ to today.

## 1. INTRODUCTION

Stellar bars play a crucial role in the secular evolution of disk galaxies. Through torques and shocks, bars can drive gas inflows to the central region, triggering star formation and building bulges and pseudobulges (e.g., Athanassoula 2003; Kormendy \& Kennicutt 2004a; Jogee et al. 2005; Sellwood 2016). Many observational studies present evidence for larger molecular gas concentrations (e.g., Sakamoto et al. 1999; Jogee et al. 2005) or enhanced star formation rates (SFRs) in the circumnuclear region of barred galaxies (e.g., Ho et al. 1997; Coelho \& Gadotti 2011; Zhou et al. 2015; Lin et al. 2020). Stellar bars can also redistribute mass and angular momentum by interacting with gas, stars, and the dark matter halo (e.g. Athanassoula 2002; Saha \& Naab 2013; Sellwood 2016; Collier et al. 2018, 2019). The connection between bar structures and the presence of active galactic nuclei (AGN) remains unclear, as both theoretical studies (e.g., Hopkins \& Quataert 2010; Smethurst et al. 2019; Kataria \& Vivek 2024) and observational studies present mixed results (e.g., Knapen et al. 1995; Buta \& Combes 1996; Cheung et al. 2015; Galloway et al. 2015; Goulding et al. 2017; Garland et al. 2023). Theoretical and observational studies show that large-scale bars do not directly fuel the AGN as bardriven gas inflows tend to stall near the inner Lindblad resonances and do not reach the central regions to fuel the AGN (e.g., Buta \& Combes 1996). In order to drive the gas further inward, other mechanisms are needed, such as nuclear bars, dynamical friction on clumps, nuclear spirals, and feedback (e.g., Shlosman et al. 1989; see review by Jogee 2006 and references therein; Hopkins \& Quataert 2010).
To understand the role of bars in galaxy evolution, it is crucial to investigate the emergence and prevalence of bars in disk galaxies at different cosmic times. Many studies have investigated barred galaxies at $z \sim 0$, and the majority of bar studies in the rest-frame nearinfrared (NIR) report that $\sim 65 \%$ of massive disk galaxies host a bar (e.g., Eskridge et al. 2000; Marinova \& Jogee 2007; Menéndez-Delmestre et al. 2007; Sheth et al. 2008; Erwin 2018).
At higher redshifts, the majority of Hubble Space Telescope (HST) studies have explored bars in the restframe optical light out to $z \sim 1$ (e.g., Abraham et al. 1999; Elmegreen et al. 2004; Jogee et al. 2004; Sheth et al. 2008; Cameron et al. 2010; Melvin et al. 2014), and results on how the observed bar fraction (defined

[^0]as the fraction of disk galaxies that are barred) varies from little variation to a strong decline. The variations on the observed bar fraction out to $z \sim 1$ depend on the stellar mass range selected (Cameron et al. 2010; Erwin 2018). The study by Simmons et al. (2014) represents a first attempt to push the explorations of bars in the restframe optical out to $z \sim 2$ and finds the observed bar fraction decreases to $\sim 5-10 \%$ at $z \sim 2$. However, the study faced difficulties identifying bars at $z>1.5$ due to the limited depth and spatial resolution of HST Wide Field Camera 3 (WFC3) F160W images. Furthermore, Erwin (2018) stresses that the decreasing bar sizes at higher redshifts can help explain some of the decreasing trends of the observed bar fraction.
The sensitive, high-resolution NIRCam images from the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST; Gardner et al. 2023) have spawned unprecedented progress in the exploration of bars at $z \gtrsim 1$. In our earlier work Guo et al. (2023), we presented the first evidence of welldeveloped bars above $z \sim 2$ and showed six examples of robustly identified bars at $z>1$ in the rest-frame NIR light from F444W images, including two bars with the highest spectroscopic redshifts known at the time ( $z \sim 2.136$ and 2.312). The six example barred galaxies shown in Guo et al. (2023) have a range of SFRs, and most of them have possible nearby companions, raising the tantalizing possibility of tidally triggered bars at early epochs. Using JWST NIRCam imaging, Costantin et al. (2023) report a barred spiral galaxy at a photometric redshift $z_{\text {phot }} \sim 3$ when the Universe was only two billion years old. Huang et al. (2023) report a discovery of a barred dusty star-forming spiral galaxy with a spectroscopic redshift $z=2.467$, confirmed both by NIRCam imaging and ALMA detection. McKinney et al. (2024) study the morphology of heavily dust-attenuated submillimeter galaxies in using JWST NIRCam imaging from COSMOS-web (Casey et al. 2023). They identify possible bar candidates out to $z \sim 3.4$. Recent studies also report "bar-like" structures in lensed galaxies: Smail et al. (2023) report an ultramassive lensed galaxy at $z_{\text {spec }}=4.26$ that has a "bar-like" structure in the central regions of the galaxy, and Amvrosiadis et al. (2024) report detection of the onset of bar formation in a gasrich lensed galaxy at $z_{\text {phot }} \sim 3.8$.
While the above individual cases of barred galaxies at early epochs are exciting, it is now time to systematically quantify the abundance of barred galaxies by measuring the observed bar fraction at $z>1$. The recent paper by Le Conte et al. (2024) (hereafter LC24) explores the rest-frame NIR bar fraction at $z \sim 1-3$ using JWST NIRCam F444W images. We note that two recently


[^0]:    * Hubble Fellow

submitted studies, Géron et al. (in prep.) and HuertasCompany et al. (2025), also present the observed bar fraction out to $z \sim 4$ or $z \sim 5$ using JWST data. Our results are consistent with their observed bar fraction. In this paper, we focus on comparing our results with LC24.
Complementing LC24, in this work, we attempt to study the abundance and properties of bars at $z \sim 0.5-$ 4. Specifically, LC24 mainly used four JWST NIRCam pointings from the Cosmic Evolution Early Release Science Survey (CEERS; Finkelstein et al. 2022) and visually inspected F444W images and radial profiles of ellipticity and position angle to identify barred galaxies at $1 \leq z \leq 3$. Our study explores the bars across a wider redshift range of $z \sim 0.5-4$ and uses all 10 CEERS NIRCam pointings to derive a large sample of 1770 galaxies with stellar mass $M_{\star}>10^{10} M_{\odot}$. We identify barred galaxies by applying two methods - visual classification and quantitative criteria applied to ellipse fits - to both F200W and F444W images. This allows us to leverage the sharper spatial resolution in F200W images to identify smaller bars and the longer rest-frame wavelength traced by F444W images to unveil obscured dusty bars and other stellar features.
Alongside the observational breakthroughs, there have been major advances on the theoretical front. New high-resolution cosmological simulations (e.g., Kraljic, Bournaud, \& Martig 2012; Scannapieco \& Athanassoula 2012; Bonoli et al. 2016; Spinoso et al. 2017; Algorry et al. 2017; Fragkoudi et al. 2021; Rosas-Guevara et al. 2020, 2022; Bi et al. 2022; Fragkoudi et al. 2025) are now probing the growth of bars and their impact on galaxy evolution out to at least $z \sim 4$. The predictions on the bar fraction are widely different: some simulations find that bars only appear after $z \sim 1$ (e.g., Kraljic et al. 2012; Algorry et al. 2017), while others find that bars already exist at $z \geq 3$ (e.g., Rosas-Guevara et al. 2022; Bi et al. 2022; Fragkoudi et al. 2025). The question of whether bars can grow in early disks that might be dynamically hot, and the impact of the dark matter fraction, feedback model, and tidal interactions on bar formation are topics of active discussion (e.g., Ghosh et al. 2023; Rosas-Guevara et al. 2022; Bi et al. 2022; Bland-Hawthorn et al. 2023;Ceverino et al. 2023; Bland-Hawthorn et al. 2024; Dekel, A., private communication).
In this paper, we push the studies of barred galaxies for the first time out to $z \sim 4$ when the Universe was $\sim 11 \%$ of its present age. We provide a comprehensive estimate of the observed bar fraction and the observed properties of stellar bars at $z \sim 0.5-4.0$, using JWST NIRCam F200W and F444W images from the CEERS
survey. Our results only apply to bars with projected semi-major axis $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ ( $\sim 2 \times$ the full width at half-maximum (FWHM) of PSF in F200W images) that can be traced by ellipse fits of our data. The observational data and sample selection are outlined in $\S 2$. In $\S 3$ we describe our multi-pronged methodology to identify disk galaxies and bars using ellipse fits, and visual classification. In $\S 4$, we present our results on the observed bar fraction using two different bar identification methods (ellipse fits and visual classification) applied to both F200W and F444W images. In section $\S 4.2$, we outline the properties (e.g., strength, sizes) of the observed bars. In $\S 4.3$, we compare the observed bar fraction to results from the TNG50 hydrodynamical simulations and the Auriga simulations to see how theoretical predictions compare to empirical results. In $\S 4.4$, we discuss how the observed bar fraction provides a lower limit to the intrinsic bar fraction due to systematic effects causing us to miss a subset of bars. In $\S 5$, we discuss the implications of our results for the early emergence of barred galaxies, theoretical models of disk galaxies, and bar-driven secular evolution of galaxies. While this paper focuses mainly on the observed bar fraction and properties, future work will explore the relationship between bars and galaxy properties (e.g., SF, bulges, AGN, and presence of companions) using a control sample of unbarred galaxies.
In this paper, we assume the latest Planck flat $\Lambda$ CDM cosmology with $\mathrm{H}_{0}=67.36, \Omega_{m}=0.3153$, and $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.6847$ (Planck Collaboration et al. 2020). All magnitudes are in the absolute bolometric system (AB; Oke \& Gunn 1983).

## 2. OBSERVATIONAL DATA AND SAMPLE SELECTION
### 2.1. CEERS NIRCam Imaging

CEERS (Finkelstein et al. 2022) is an early-release science program that surveys $50 \%$ of the Extended Groth Strip (EGS) previously covered by the Cosmic Assembly Near-infrared Deep Extragalactic Legacy Survey (CANDELS; Grogin et al. 2011; Koekemoer et al. 2011). We focus on the 10 NIRCam pointings covering roughly 88 square arcminutes (corresponding to a comoving volume of $\sim 960000 \mathrm{Mpc}^{3}$ at $z \sim 0.5-4$ ) of the area of the CANDELS EGS in seven bands: F115W, F150W, F200W, F277W, F356W, F410M, and F444W. The total exposure time for pixels observed in all three dithers was typically 2835 s per band, corresponding to a $5 \sigma$ depth ranging from 28.8 to 29.7 (Bagley et al. 2023).

CEERS latest public data release 0.5 (including NIRCam pointings $1,2,3,6$ ) and data release 0.6 (including NIRCam pointings $4,5,7,8,9,10$ ) are used in

this study. The reduction of the NIRCam images is performed using version 1.8.5 of the JWST Calibration Pipeline with some custom modifications. For details on the reduction steps, see (Bagley et al. 2023). The final mosaics for each pointing in all bands have pixel scales of $0^{\prime \prime} 03 /$ pixel. The publicly released mosaics are available at ceers.github.io/dr06.html and on MAST via 10.17909/z7p0-8481. We used an internal photometry catalog in this study, and the catalog was produced by using Source Extractor (Bertin \& Arnouts 1996) v2.25.0 in two image mode, with an inverse-variance weighted combination of the PSF-matched F277W and F356W images as the detection image, and photometry measured on all seven bands.

### 2.2. Sample Selection

We start with a sample of galaxies with stellar mass $M_{\star}>10^{10} M_{\odot}$ at $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$. Sources are identified in an internal photometry catalog with photometric redshifts provided by the CEERS team. The same catalog is used and discussed in Finkelstein et al. (2024). The authors of the catalog estimate photometric redshifts were estimated with eazy (Brammer et al. 2008), following the methodology in Finkelstein et al. (2023), and including the additional templates from Larson et al. (2023).

We use the stellar mass measurements provided by the CEERS team (Iyer et al. in prep.). We briefly summarize below the approach used by the authors: the authors of the catalog estimate stellar masses are estimated for all objects in the catalog using the Dense Basis ${ }^{1}$ (Iyer et al. 2019). The code performs a fully Bayesian inference of the star formation history (SFH), dust attenuation, and chemical enrichment for each galaxy using a fully non-parametric Gaussian process-based description for the SFH described in Iyer et al. (2019). The model uses a Chabrier IMF (Chabrier 2003), Calzetti dust attenuation law (Calzetti et al. 2000), and Madau IGM absorption (Madau 1995). Setting explicit priors in SFH space using non-parametric SFHs has been shown to be robust against outshining due to younger stellar populations that otherwise bias estimates of masses and star formation rates (e.g., Iyer \& Gawiser 2017; Leja et al. 2019; Lower et al. 2020).

The deep CEERS NIRCam imaging has $5 \sigma$ depth ranging from 28.8 to 29.7 AB magnitude across all bands and pointings (Bagley et al. 2023). Using the approach described in Pozzetti et al. (2010), we estimate that $10^{10}$ $M_{\odot}$ is well above the $90 \%$ stellar mass complete limit

The stellar mass and redshifts selection results in a sample of 1770 massive galaxies with $M_{\star}>10^{10} M_{\odot}$ at redshifts $z \sim 0.5-4$, with $328(0.5 \leq z<1.0), 448$ $(1.0 \leq z<1.5), 395(1.5 \leq z<2.0), 393(2.0 \leq z<3.0)$, and $206(3.0 \leq z \leq 4.0)$ galaxies in each redshift bin.
We supplement photometric redshifts with available published spectroscopic redshifts in EGS (N. Hathi 2022, private communication) and spectroscopic redshifts derived from JWST NIRSpec observations (Arrabal Haro et al. 2023; Arrabal Haro et al. 2024, in prep.). We find $\sim 55 \%$ of sources have an available spectroscopic redshift. If a source has more than one spectroscopic redshift measurement, we choose the one with the highest quality. Using the sources with known spectroscopic redshifts, we estimate the normalized median absolute deviation $\left(\sigma_{\text {NMAD }}{ }^{2}\right)$ of photometric redshifts to be $\sim 0.04$. We note that sources with spectroscopic redshifts are mainly $z \lesssim 3$ sources and are, on average, $\sim 1$ magnitude brighter (in the F356W band) compared to the rest of the sources that only have photometric redshifts.

## 3. METHODOLOGY

In this work, we refer to the bar fraction directly measured from observations as the "observed bar fraction" to distinguish it from the true or "intrinsic bar fraction" discussed in § 4.4 of this paper. The intrinsic and observed bar fractions may differ due to many reasons, including systematic effects that cause a subset of bars to be missed in the observations. The observed bar fraction in this paper is analogous to the "bar fraction" reported in previous observational studies.
The observed bar fraction $f_{\text {bar }}$ is defined as the fraction of disk galaxies that are observed to have stellar bars:

$$
f_{\text {bar }}=\frac{N_{\text {bar }}}{N_{\text {disk }}}
$$

where $N_{\text {disk }}$ is the sample size of the moderately inclined disk galaxies and $N_{\text {bar }}$ is the number of barred galaxies identified in the sample of moderately inclined disk galaxies.
Disk galaxies are considered to be systems with an extended outer disk. In the local $z \sim 0$ universe, disk galaxies can be further classified into Hubble types, including S0, Sa, Sb, Sc, Sd, and Sm/ Irr. At higher redshifts, Hubble types are not well-defined, and therefore we do not further classify disk galaxies into Hubble types. We discuss the identification of disk galaxies in § 3.1 and the identification of bars in § 3.2.

### 3.1. Sample of Moderately Inclined Disk Galaxies

We first select disks of all inclinations from visual classification in § 3.1.1 and then apply the axis ratios obtained in § 3.1.2 to select the sample of moderately inclined $\left(i \leq 65^{\circ}\right)$ disk galaxies.

### 3.1.1. Identification of Disk Galaxies via Visual Classification

The primary goal of visual classification is to identify disk galaxies (including disks of all inclinations).
Three authors of this study (Y.G., E.W., K.P.) classified all the 1770 galaxies. Before visual classifications, we trained our classifiers with detailed materials, including the latest results from recent JWST studies (e.g., Ferreira et al. 2022a; Jacobs et al. 2022; Kartaltepe et al. 2023). Each classifier was asked to visually inspect postage stamps of seven $4 \frown 0 \times 4 \frown 0$ cutouts in NIRCam F115W, F150W, F200W, F277W, F356W, F410M and F444W images, for each of our 1770 sample galaxies at $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$. At $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$, postage stamps show the rest-frame optical and NIR morphology for each source, allowing the classifiers to utilize as much information as possible. The classifiers are asked to select one main morphology class for each galaxy from the following options:

- Disk Galaxies: This category contains all galaxies that have an extended outer disk component. The outer disk is identified as an outer component with a slowly declining surface brightness profile. It surrounds the central region of the galaxy, which can often host bulges with a more steeply declining surface brightness profile. Galaxies in this category can contain other components (e.g., a spheroid component, such as a classical bulge) or be weakly interacting (disks are slightly distorted but are still identifiable and well-resolved). Inclined disk galaxies are included in this category.
- Pure Spheroidal Galaxies: The category contains galaxies that are only spheroids without an outer disk. An example at $z \sim 0$ would be a classical elliptical galaxy.
- Strongly Asymmetric/Distorted Galaxies: The category contains galaxies that are dominated by strongly distorted or asymmetric features. These are typically indicative of strongly interacting galaxies at these epochs.
- Unclassifiable Sources: This category includes unresolved sources, sources located in regions with image defects in F200W or F444W images, overdeblended sources, or artifacts.

A galaxy is considered to be a visually classified disk galaxy if at least two out of three classifiers classify it in the "Disk Galaxies" category. The number of disks selected from visual classifications are shown in Figure 2 (dark blue bars), corresponding to a disk fraction of $\sim$ $74 \%, 75 \%, 70 \%, 66 \%$, and $63 \%$ at $z \sim 0.5-1.0,1.0-1.5$, $1.5-2.0,2.0-3.0$ and $3.0-4.0$, respectively.
These values are reasonably consistent with the fraction of disk galaxies reported in previous studies (e.g., Tamburri et al. 2014; Kartaltepe et al. 2023; Ferreira et al. 2022b; Lee et al. 2023; Huertas-Company et al. 2024), taking into account the different stellar mass ranges used and the variations in criteria for classifying a disk galaxy in the aforementioned studies.

### 3.1.2. Characterizing Disk Galaxies via Sérsic Fits

We use the structural measurements measured using GALFIT (Peng et al. 2010) from McGrath et al. (in prep.). Here, we briefly summarize the approach used by the authors: GALFIT v3.0.5 was run individually on each of the six broadband bands using the background-subtracted version of the CEERS imaging mosaics. Empirical PSFs, generated by stacking stars

across all CEERS fields (Finkelstein et al. 2022), were used as input to Galfit. Corresponding thumbnails of the ERR array (see Bagley et al. (2023) for details) are used as input noise maps (i.e., "sigma images") for each source in GALFIT. Single component Sérsic fitting was performed for all selected sources with stellar mass $\gtrsim$ $10^{7} M_{\odot}$. During fitting, the background value was fixed at zero, and constraints were applied.
We use the axis ratio measurements $(b / a)$ from single component Sérsic fits (McGrath et al. (in prep.)) to estimate the inclination ( $i$ ) of each galaxy, using the conversion $\cos ^{2} i=(b / a)^{2}$. We assume the intrinsic axis ratio of a disk galaxy to be 1 . We define a galaxy to have a moderate inclination ( $i \leq 65^{\circ}$ ) in our sample if the disk galaxy has an axis ratio $>0.42$ in at least one of the F277W, F356W, and F444W fits. Previous bar studies commonly adopt $i>65^{\circ}$ (e.g., Díaz-García et al. 2016; Erwin 2018 or $i>60^{\circ}$ (e.g., Jogee et al. 2004; Sheth et al. 2008; Guo et al. 2023) as the inclination cut.
Using the fits, we exclude disk galaxies with inclination $i>65^{\circ}$ from the visually classified disk galaxies sample. This results in the exclusion of approximately one-third of disk galaxies in each redshift bin. The resulting number of moderately inclined disk galaxies in each redshift bin is shown in Figure 2 (cyan bars). We obtain a sample of 839 moderately inclined disk galaxies.
In this paper, we identify disks via visual classification (§3.1.1). We perform an additional test on our methodology by inspecting the distribution of Sérsic indices from McGrath et al. (in prep.) for our sample of disk galaxies. We find the distribution is similar to that in previous studies (e.g., Kartaltepe et al. 2023) with the median Sérsic index at $\mathrm{n} \sim 1.6_{-0.6}^{+0.8}$, with the range defined by the 25 th and 75 th percentiles.

### 3.2. Bar Identification

Stellar bars can be identified via different methods such as visual classification (e.g., de Vaucouleurs et al. 1991; Masters et al. 2010; Simmons et al. 2014), Fourier decomposition (e.g., Athanassoula et al. 1990; RosasGuevara et al. 2020, 2022), 2-D structural decomposition of the galaxy surface brightness distribution (e.g., Laurikainen et al. 2005; Weinzirl et al. 2009; Gadotti et al. 2015) or ellipse fits of galaxy images (e.g., Jedrzejewski 1987; Wozniak et al. 1995; Jogee et al. 1999, 2002, 2004; Knapen et al. 2000; Elmegreen et al. 2004; Erwin 2005; Marinova \& Jogee 2007; Menéndez-Delmestre et al. 2007; Sheth et al. 2008; Guo et al. 2023). In this paper, we adopt two methods, ellipse fits and visual classification, and we discuss the details for each method in § 3.2.2 and § 3.2.3 respectively.
3.2.1. Leveraging Both F200W and F444W Images

This figure illustrates the classification of disk galaxies following the methodology in § 3.1 and shows the number of galaxies during different stages of the classification process. We start with all galaxies (gray), visually identify disk galaxies (dark blue), and subselect moderately inclined disk galaxies with $i \leq 65^{\circ}$ (cyan). In each redshift bin, about one-third of disk galaxies are removed because of high inclination $\left(i>65^{\circ}\right)$.

For this work, we use both F200W and F444W images as the sharper spatial resolution in F200W images allows us to identify smaller bars while the longer rest-frame wavelength traced by F444W images can unveil dustobscured stellar features.
At $z \sim 0.5$ to 4 , the rest-frame wavelengths traced by F444W images range from $\sim 0.9 \mu \mathrm{~m}$ to $\sim 3 \mu \mathrm{~m}$ (see Table 1). The rest-frame optical-red light and NIR light are effective tracers of stellar mass and are less affected by dust and star formation, so they can better trace stellar structures than rest-frame UV or optical-blue light (e.g., Frogel et al. 1996; Meidt et al. 2014; Suess et al. 2022; Ren et al. 2024). Figure 1 in Guo et al. (2023) illustrates the effect of changing the rest-frame wavelength, in which the bar structure appears more evident in its F444W image compared to shorter wavelength bands. Furthermore, previous studies at $z \sim 0$ have shown that the NIR bar fraction is higher than the optical bar fraction (e.g., Marinova \& Jogee 2007; Menéndez-Delmestre et al. 2007).

However, the FWHM of the PSF in F444W images is $0 . \prime 163$, providing a spatial resolution of $\sim 1.2-1.4 \mathrm{kpc}$ across $z \sim 0.5$ to 4 (see Table 1), which implies that short stellar bars will likely be missed in our classifications as roughly two resolution elements ( $\gtrsim 2.4 \mathrm{kpc}$ ) are generally required along the semi-major length of the bar for a robust bar identification (e.g., Erwin 2018; Liang et al. 2024). Consequently, a fraction of bars may be missed in the F444W images, and we will underestimate the observed bar fraction. Therefore, as a complementary approach, we choose to estimate the bar fraction in the F200W images, in which the PSF FWHM is only $0^{\prime \prime} 08$ (corresponding to $\sim 0.6-$ 0.7 kpc across $z \sim 0.5-4$, see Table 1). As ellipse fits can robustly detect bars with projected semi-major axis $a_{\text {bar }} \gtrsim 2 \times$ PSF FWHM, with F200W images, we expect to robustly detect $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$. We note that across the redshift range $z \sim 4$ to 0.5 , the rest-frame wavelength in F200W images changes from $\gtrsim 4000 \AA$ to NIR, thereby tracing different stellar populations. We do not attempt to go beyond $z \sim 4$ because at these higher redshifts, our JWST NIRCam F200W images would trace the rest-frame UV light, which is not an effective tracer of the stellar potential and stellar bars, and primarily traces hot young massive stars.

### 3.2.2. Bar Identification via Ellipse Fits

The detailed methodology of identifying barred galaxies via ellipse fits is described in Jogee et al. (2004) and Marinova \& Jogee (2007). This method has already been proven effective for bars at higher redshifts in our pilot study Guo et al. (2023). In this work, we followed the

methodology based on Guo et al. (2023). Here we briefly summarize the main steps:

We fitted ellipses to the F200W image and F444W image of each of the 839 moderately inclined disk galaxies. The cutout images being fitted are $6^{\prime \prime} 0 \times 6^{\prime \prime} 0$. For specific cases, when necessary, nearby sources were masked. Then we ran "isophote.Ellipse.fit_image" Photutils from Python's astropy package (Bradley et al. 2020) twice, following the two steps outlined in $\S 4.1$ of Guo et al. (2023). ### 3.2.3. Bar Identification via Visual Classification

We employ the visual classification of bars as a method that is complementary to the identification of bars via ellipse fits. In rest-frame optical and NIR images, a stellar bar visually appears as an elongated bright feature that extends from the central region of the galaxy into the outer disk. While visual classification may be less objective and quantitative, it leverages the power of the eye to capture a wide range of details in the image that can impact bar and disk identification, such as asymmetric features, clumps, inclined rings, and companions.

We asked the classifiers to visually identify barred galaxies in F200W and F444W images separately. When classifying a galaxy as unbarred or barred, we assign a confidence score ranging from 0 to 3 to characterize the robustness and degree of confidence of the classification. The scores are defined as 3 (clearly barred), 2 (likely barred), 1 (likely unbarred), and 0 (clearly unbarred):

- A score of 3 (clearly barred) is assigned if an image shows a clear bar residing in a low-to-moderately inclined disk galaxy.
- A score of 2 (likely barred) rather than a score of 3 (clearly barred) is assigned if an image shows a likely bar, but complicating factors prevent a foolproof identification. Examples of complicating factors include the bar feature being small, the presence of nearby clumps, or the disk being close to the inclination limit.
- A score of 1 (likely unbarred) rather than a score of 2 (likely barred) or a score of 0 (clearly unbarred) is assigned if nearly all visual indicators suggest there is no bar, but there are some mildly elongated central structures that we cannot completely rule out as potentially being weak bars.
- A score of 0 (clearly unbarred) is assigned if an image does not show any evidence of a bar.

We combined the visual classification results from all three classifiers and took the average score. In this work, we report a source as a barred galaxy robustly identified via visual classification if the average score $\geq 1.33$, corresponding to two out of the three classifiers deciding the source has a score of 2 or higher.

In this section, we report three observed bar fractions ( $f_{\text {bar }}$ ) based on ellipse fits: $f_{\text {bar }}$ based on F200W images, $f_{\text {bar }}$ based on F444W images, and the overall $f_{\text {bar }}$ based on bars identified in either band.

Each of the $f_{\text {bar }}$ is derived following $f_{\text {bar }}=N_{\text {bar }} / N_{\text {disk }}$ (Equation 1; see § 3), while $N_{\text {bar }}$ and $N_{\text {disk }}$ are different for each measurement. For the bar fraction based on the F200W or F444W images, $N_{\text {bar }}$ is based on bars identified via fits in that band, and $N_{\text {disk }}$ is the number of moderately inclined disk galaxies that have successful fits in that band, respectively. The overall bar fraction

is based on bars identified via fits of either band and $N_{\text {disk }}$ is the number of disk galaxies that have successful fits in either band.
As stated earlier in § 3.2.1, the sharper F200W images (Table 1) are effective at tracing small bars, while the longer-wavelength F444W images may more effectively trace bars that are obscured by dust or impacted by recent star formation. Therefore, the overall $f_{\text {bar }}$ is the best measure because it accounts for the advantages in the individual measurements and captures most bars.
One limitation of using ellipse fits to derive the observed bar fraction is that not all disk galaxies had successful fits. Columns 2 and 3 in Table 2 present the $N_{\text {disk }}$ that have successful fits in each redshift bin for each band, and column 4 shows the $N_{\text {disk }}$ identified via visual classification. The ellipse fits tend to fail in galaxies that have a low average signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), clumpy structures inside the disks, or peculiar features in the outer region of the disk. At $z>2$, the shorter-wavelength F200W images are more sensitive to dust and star formation and, hence, are more likely to show clumpy, discontinuous light distribution in star-forming galaxies. Therefore, even if a galaxy can be visually classified as a disk galaxy, it may not be successfully ellipse-fitted, especially in the F200W images. The inability to fit all galaxies has been reported in some previous studies using the ellipse fitting technique (e.g., Jogee et al. 2004; Marinova \& Jogee 2007; Le Conte et al. 2024). Barred galaxies identified via visual classification can be missed in the selection of bars identified via ellipse fits due to the failure of ellipse fitting.

It is to be noted that the definition of strong and weak bars in LC24 is significantly different from that used in most bar studies where the properties of the bar (e.g., ellipticity, shape, length, mass, Qb) are used to define its strength, rather than the votes of classifiers. Following the strategy used in our pilot paper, we first adopt the widely used definition that the bar length is the length of the semi-major axis (sma) $a_{\epsilon}$ where ellipticity smoothly rises to a maximum value along the bar (e.g., Athanassoula \& Misiriotis 2002; Jogee et al. 2004; Marinova \& Jogee 2007; Menéndez-Delmestre et al. 2007; Guo et al. 2023). Therefore, given the nature of this definition, we note that this method can underestimate the bar length because the maximum ellipticity we select is always close to the end of the bar but still inside the bar. Also, some studies (e.g., Athanassoula \& Misiriotis 2002; Martinez-Valpuesta et al. 2006) find that this definition can underestimate the true bar length. We, therefore, take $a_{\epsilon}$ as the lower limit of the bar length measurement.

For the upper limit of the bar length measurement, we adopt the method used in Erwin (2005), where the projected bar length $a_{\text {upper }}$ is defined as the minimum of two measures: the first minimum in ellipticity outside the bar's peak ellipticity, or the point at which the position angles of the fitted ellipses differ by $\geq 10^{\circ}$ from the bar's position angle. This method combines two common bar length definitions that use a drop of ellipticity and the change of PA to define the bar length. While $a_{\epsilon}$ is more sensitive to the transition from the bulgedominated region to the bar-dominated region, the other is more sensitive to the transition from the end of the bar to the outer disk. As shown in Erwin (2005), this definition can sometimes overestimate the bar length, especially when there are no spiral arms present. However, this definition well served the purpose of giving an upper limit for measuring the bar length in our study.

We stress that bar lengths measured using different definitions in this study are the projected bar lengths. The exploration of deprojected bar lengths is beyond the scope of the current study. The deprojection process requires improved knowledge (e.g., on the thickness of the galactic disk and the thickness of the bar) and tests in this new redshift regime and will be the topic of future work.

### 4.4. Impact of Redshift-Dependent Systematic Effects on Observed Bar Fraction

We presented the overall observed bar fraction derived from ellipse fits and from visual classification in § 4.1.3, and found the observed bar fraction declines from $z \sim$ 0.5 to $z \sim 4$. If taken at face value, this would suggest that disk galaxies hosting bars become increasingly rare at early epochs (with only $\sim 2.4 \%-6.4 \%$ of disk galaxies being barred at $z \sim 3.5$ ). However, we stress that the observed bar fraction may be a lower limit to the intrinsic bar fraction due to observation-limited redshiftdependent systematic effects (e.g., impact of PSF, cosmological SB dimming of the outer disk, impact of dust and recent SF, and high-redshift features that complicate traditional bar identification) that cause us to miss bars in our analyses.
The spatial resolution, which is limited by the PSF FWHM, is one of the main factors. The limited spatial resolution will cause both visual classification and ellipse fits to miss small bars. Studies of bars at $z \sim$ 0 are less affected by the PSF and often can reach a spatial resolution of $\sim 0.2-0.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ (e.g., Marinova \& Jogee 2007; Menéndez-Delmestre et al. 2007; Buta et al. 2015). Erwin (2018) has carefully compared the observed bar fraction at $z \sim 0$ from SDSS (e.g., Skibba et al. 2012; Cheung et al. 2013) and from Spitzer based studies ( $\mathrm{S}_{4} \mathrm{G}$ ) (e.g., Buta et al. 2015; Díaz-García et al. 2016) and found that the different spatial resolution of different instruments accounts for the discrepancy in the observed bar fractions. In our analyses, we try to mitigate the effect of PSF by looking at the observed bar fraction in F200W images, whose PSF FWHM corresponds to $\sim 0.6-0.7 \mathrm{kpc}$ at $z \sim 0.5-4$. Ellipse fits can effectively identify bars with $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5-2$ times the PSF, and the F200W images allow us to robustly identify bars with $a_{\text {bar }} \gtrsim 1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$.
If we assume that the sizes of bars at $z \sim 0$ (e.g., Erwin 2018) were unchanged at higher redshifts, then in our sample containing disk galaxies at $M_{\star}>10^{10} M_{\odot}$ we would expect over $90 \%$ of bars would have bar lengths greater than $\sim 1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ (see Figure 8 in Erwin (2018)) and such bars would likely to be picked up by the NIRCam F200W images.
However, given the evolution in disk sizes (e.g., van der Wel et al. 2014; Ward et al. 2024), with disks becoming smaller from $z \sim 0.5$ to $z \sim 3-4$ by $\sim 40-$ $60 \%$, we might reasonably expect bars to become smaller at earlier epochs. It is hard to predict the exact impact of disk evolution on bar lengths as the ratio of bar length to disk size has a wide range of values at $z \sim 0\left(a_{\text {bar }} / R_{25} \sim 0.1-0.8\right.$ and $a_{\text {bar }} / h \sim 0.2-1$; see Marinova \& Jogee 2007, Gadotti 2011 and Erwin 2018).

For the sake of argument, we use the $R_{e}$ measurements from McGrath et al. (in prep.) and assume $R_{e}$ measurements are about one-third of the $R_{25}$ measurements (e.g., Leroy et al. 2021) to get the distribution of $R_{25}$ for our disk galaxies at $z \sim 2-4$. Then, we assume a median bar-to-disk length $\left(a_{\text {bar }} / R_{25}\right)$ of $\sim 0.4$ to estimate the distribution of bar lengths at $z \sim 2-4$. According to this roughly estimated distribution, $\sim 50 \%$ of the bars would have $a_{\text {bar }}<1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ at $z \sim 2-4$ and thus not be robustly detected by F200W images.
Another factor that can affect bar identification at high redshifts is the cosmic surface brightness (CSB) dimming of the outer disk. CSB dimming can cause the outer disk to be increasingly dimmed (factor of $\sim(1+z)^{-4}$ ) at higher redshifts, and if this prevents the outer disk from being clearly identifiable, the bar-disk transition will not be evident and the barred galaxy may be misidentified (e.g., Jogee et al. (2002)). We try to restrict this effect by applying a stellar mass cut where we can focus on more massive sources, which are, in general, brighter according to the mass-luminosity relation. Nevertheless, we note that cases of barred galaxies can be missed because of the faint disks. One example is the barred galaxy at $z \sim 3$ reported in Costantin et al. (2023). The galaxy is not classified as a barred galaxy during visual classifications (Kartaltepe et al. 2023) but is later identified when using quantitative methods like stacking, ellipse fitting, and multi-component image fitting. Liang et al. (2024) explored a set of artificially redshifted DESI images observed in JWST CEERS and pointed out that the impact of dimming and noise on bar identification is not significant when the disk galaxy in CEERS has $M_{\star}>10^{9.75} M_{\odot}$ at $z<3$. Thus, we might not expect surface brightness dimming of the outer disk to have a large effect on bar identification in massive galaxies at $z<3$, but this effect may get increasingly important at higher redshifts. Nonetheless, more investigation on the effect of CSB dimming is needed.
The effect of dust and star formation has been addressed to some extent by our strategy of independently deriving observed bar fractions in F200W and F444W images. Even though the rest-frame optical light can be blocked by dust the rest-frame NIR light can penetrate through the dust, revealing the stellar structure that is predominately composed of lower-mass stars (e.g., Frogel et al. 1996; Meidt et al. 2014; Suess et al. 2022). However, due to the loss of resolution in the F444W images, it is unavoidable that dust-obscured short bars ( $\lesssim$ 2.4 kpc ) fail to be identified in both F200W and F444W images. However, we note that the impact of recent SF may not be a dominant factor in missing strong bars as both observational studies and theoretical simulations
show that SF does not tend to happen along strong bars (e.g., James et al. 2009; James \& Percival 2016; Donohoe-Keyes et al. 2019).
While we have discussed many systematic effects that can cause us to miss bars and underestimate the bar fraction, it is important to note that some factors can also cause us to overestimate the bar fraction. For example, both ellipse fitting and visual classification can lead to falsely classified bars by mistaking other features, such as clumps or merging events for bars, due to the limited resolution and wavelength range of the observations we have. To firmly confirm the existence of high-redshift bars, follow-up observations on galaxy kinematics are needed.

### 4.5. Nearby Neighbors of Barred Galaxies

Bars can form spontaneously in isolated disks or be induced by minor mergers or tidal interactions (e.g., Hernquist \& Mihos 1995; Izquierdo-Villalba et al. 2022; Bi et al. 2022; Ansar et al. 2023). In the pilot paper Guo et al. (2023), we noted that the majority of the six barred galaxies at $1.1 \leq z \leq 2.3$ shown in the paper appear to have nearby sources that could be potential companions.
Similarly, many barred galaxies identified in this paper also appear to have nearby neighbors (e.g., CEERS86093 in Figure 4). For a sample of barred galaxies (robustly identified via at least one method in at least one band; see $\S 4.1 .1$ and $\S 4.1 .2$ ) and a control sample of moderately inclined unbarred disk galaxies, we calculate the proportion of galaxies that show at least one nearby source within an angular separation of $2 \ f^{\prime} 5$ (corresponding to $\sim 20-23 \mathrm{kpc}$ at $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$ ) and with $|\Delta z /(1+z)|<\sigma_{\text {NMAD }}\left(z_{\text {phot }}\right) \sim 0.04$.

At $z<1.5$, we find that the proportion of barred galaxies with nearby sources $(43.0 \pm 3.1 \%)$ is not statistically different from that of unbarred disk galaxies $(38.9 \pm 1.8 \%)$. However, at $z \geq 1.5$, the proportion of barred galaxies with nearby sources $(55.6 \pm 5.0 \%)$ appears to be statistically different from that of unbarred disk galaxies ( $37.1 \pm 1.5 \%$ ), as indicated by the chisquared test resulting in a p-value $\sim 0.01$.
These preliminary results raise the tantalizing possibility that at early epochs ( $z \geq 1.5$ ), bars may preferentially form in tidally interacting galaxies. This scenario would be consistent with the idea that at early epochs, it may be harder for bars to form spontaneously in isolated disk galaxies as these early disk galaxies may have properties that are not conducive to bar formation, such as being dynamically hot and hosting gas and stars with high turbulence and velocity dispersions. However, a more detailed analysis of tidally induced features and

supplement spectroscopic redshifts may be needed to conclude that bars at high redshifts tend to form via tidal interaction.
At present, we present these results as preliminary until we are able to conduct a more thorough analysis. This would include a more detailed comparison of the target and control samples, multiple methods to identify potential companions, an inspection of potential tidally induced features in the putative galaxy pairs, and the inclusion of spectroscopic redshifts for the faint neighbors to confirm that they are real companions.

## 5. DISCUSSION

In this section, we discuss the potential implications of the results presented in section $\S 4$.

### 5.1. The Emergence of Barred Galaxies at $z \sim 3-4$

Our observational results apply mainly to bars with projected semi-major axis $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ ( $\gtrsim 2 \times \mathrm{PSF}$ of F200W images) that can be robustly traced by ellipse fits of our data. For such bars, the bar fraction at $z \sim$ $2-4$ is low, with values $\sim 9 \%$ at $z \sim 2.5$ and $\lesssim 6 \%$ at $z \sim 3.5$. However, redshift-dependent systematic effects (e.g., PSF, SB dimming, dust, SF; § 4.4) might cause us to miss a subset of bars. Furthermore, at $z \sim 2-$ 4 , compared to our results, TNG50 simulations show a significantly larger bar fraction due to a large population of small bars with $a_{\text {bar }}<1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ that our data cannot robustly trace. If such a population exists, the true bar fraction may be significantly higher than our observed bar fraction.
If the true bar fraction is low at $z>2$, it would support the idea that most of the disks at $z>2$ have properties that are not conducive to bar formation or survival. These properties include being dynamically hot, turbulent, and having thick disks (e.g., Genzel et al. 2011; Pillepich et al. 2019; Wisnioski et al. 2019; Birkin et al. 2023; Hamilton-Campos et al. 2023). Inside dynamically hot (thick) disks, bar formation can be suppressed or delayed (e.g., Kraljic et al. 2012; Sheth et al. 2012; Aumer \& Binney 2017; Ghosh et al. 2023), leading to a low intrinsic bar fraction at $z>2$, when the Universe was $\lesssim 4$ billion years old.
Conversely, if the true bar fraction is high (e.g., as suggested by the TNG50 simulations; see Fig 11), then it would suggest early disks are quite susceptible to bar formation. It is notable that some high-redshift massive dynamically cold disk galaxies have been reported (e.g., Neeleman et al. 2023; Kohandel et al. 2023).
The very existence of bars at these early epochs challenges and constrains many theoretical models of disk and bar evolution. The predictions on bar fraction are
widely different: some simulations find that bars only appear after $z \sim 1$ (e.g., Kraljic et al. 2012; Algorry et al. 2017), while others find that bars already exist at $z \gtrsim 3$ (e.g., Rosas-Guevara et al. 2022; Bi et al. 2022; Fragkoudi et al. 2025). Our observations support the models where at least some bars form earlier in the disks.
Bland-Hawthorn et al. (2024) discussed that when the baryonic mass is dominant in the inner disk, turbulent gas can lead to a shorter bar formation timescale, but they also find that the presence of the high fraction of gas weakens the strength and length of the bar, or even transforms the bar to a central bulge. The fraction of baryonic mass can also play an important role in the early formation of bars. Bland-Hawthorn et al. (2023) studied the effect of disk mass fraction, defined as "the ratio of disk mass to total galaxy mass within the radius at which the rotation curve roughly peaks," on bar formation. Their findings imply that if the disk mass fraction $\gtrsim 0.3$, barred galaxies would be common at $z \sim 1-3$ if the host disk galaxies are not dominated by massive central bulges. Fragkoudi et al. (2025) also pointed out the importance of baryon dominance in bar formation, with barred galaxies on average being more baryon-dominated from high redshift down to $z \sim 0$ in the Auriga simulations.

### 5.2. Formation Mode of Bars

Simulations and theoretical models show that bars can form through spontaneous $\mathrm{m}=2$ instabilities in isolated galaxies (e.g., Efstathiou et al. 1982; Hernquist \& Mihos 1995; Athanassoula et al. 1990; Kormendy \& Kennicutt 2004b; Ansar et al. 2023) or be induced via tidal interactions (e.g.,Izquierdo-Villalba et al. 2022; Bi et al. 2022; Ansar et al. 2023). Rotationally supported massive cold stellar disks are prone to spontaneous instability (e.g., Efstathiou et al. 1982; Ghosh et al. 2021). At higher redshifts, when conditions for spontaneous bar formation are unfavorable, tidally induced bar formation can be particularly important. Especially, several theoretical studies find many of the bars form in interacting systems at high redshifts (e.g., Romano-Díaz et al. 2008; Peschken \& Lokas 2019; Bi et al. 2022; IzquierdoVillalba et al. 2022).
In § 4.5, it is especially interesting that we found that compared to a control sample of unbarred galaxies, a larger fraction of barred galaxies at $z \gtrsim 1.5$ appear to have nearby apparent neighbors or/and show signs of tidal interaction. This raises the interesting possibility that early bars may be tidally triggered, but more detailed future work using a control sample of unbarred galaxies and spectroscopic redshifts will be needed to confirm this result.

### 5.3. Evolution and Impact of Barred Galaxies Over Time

The observed bar fraction (see Figure 7), the bar fraction predicted by TNG50 simulations for bars with $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$, and the bar fraction from the Auriga simulations (see Figure 11) rise over time.
The increasing bar fraction may be the result of bars needing some time to form and grow large enough to be detectable. Different theoretical models predict bars form on a range of timescales, ranging from $\sim 1$ Gyr (e.g., Bland-Hawthorn et al. 2024) to $\sim 2-5$ Gyr (e.g., Saha \& Naab 2013). Therefore, as bars start to emerge at $z \sim 2-4$ (corresponding to a lookback time $\sim 10.5-$ 12.0 Gyr), a substantial fraction of bars should have been formed by $z \sim 0.5-1$ (corresponding to a lookback time $\sim 5.0-8.0 \mathrm{Gyr}$ ), as observed in our study.
Additionally, the timescale of bar formation depends on whether the stellar disk is dynamically cold (e.g., Ghosh et al. 2021), the properties (e.g., concentration, velocity dispersion) of gas in the disk (e.g., BlandHawthorn et al. 2024), and the properties (e.g., mass, size, spin) of the dark matter halo (e.g., Athanassoula 2003; Weinberg \& Katz 2007; Saha \& Naab 2013). As time progresses, the stellar disk becomes dynamically colder, the gas fraction decreases, and the baryon fraction in the central region increases, all leading to disks being more prone to a relatively quick formation of bars.
The lifetime of the bars can further complicate the observed evolution in the bar fraction over time. Some simulations (e.g., Ghosh et al. 2023; Ansar et al. 2023; Fragkoudi et al. 2025) and observations (e.g., Gadotti et al. 2015; de Lorenzo-Cáceres et al. 2019) suggest that some bars may be long-lived. However, other simulations show that under certain conditions, bars can also be destroyed or weakened by a larger central mass concentration (e.g., Shen \& Sellwood 2004; Athanassoula et al. 2005), by episodic gas accretion (e.g., Bournaud \& Combes 2002), or by major mergers or minor mergers (e.g., Ghosh et al. 2021). It is possible that some of the bars we observed are transient in young disks, and the transience of bars lowers the possibility of bars being observed in relatively short time intervals (e.g., the highest redshift bin $3 \leq z \leq 4$ corresponds to a mere 0.6 Gyr).
Bars drive the secular evolution of galaxies by efficiently fueling the gas to the central region, enhancing SF, and building bulges. As the bar fraction rises over time from $z \sim 4$ to today, bar-driven secular evolution of galaxies becomes an increasingly important mechanism at later times $(z<1)$. At an earlier time $(z>2)$, when the Universe was less than 4 billion years old, alternative mechanisms, such as gas accretion (e.g., Katz
et al. 2003; Kereš et al. 2005, 2012; Dekel \& Birnboim 2006; Faucher-Giguère \& Kereš 2011), galaxy mergers and tidal interactions (e.g., Conselice et al. 2003; Kartaltepe et al. 2007; Jogee et al. 2009; Lotz et al. 2010), likely played a dominant role in the growth and morphological transformation of galaxies.

## 6. SUMMARY

Over two decades, studies based on $H S T$ and now with $J W S T$ have pushed the explorations of barred galaxies from $z \sim 0$ to $z \sim 4$. Most $H S T$ results go out to $z \sim 1.2$ and are mainly based on rest-frame optical images. At $z>1.5$, two of the earliest $J W S T$ bar fraction studies include LC24 and our study going out to $z \sim 4$ based on visual classification and ellipse fits of both F200W and F444W images with quantitative criteria.
In this work, we use JWST CEERS data to present the first estimate of the observed bar fraction and bar properties out to $z \sim 4$ when the Universe was $\sim 11 \%$ of its present age. We analyze a sample of 1770 galaxies with $M_{\star}>10^{10} M_{\odot}$ and identify barred galaxies from 839 moderately inclined disk galaxies via ellipse fits and visual classification using the F200W and F444W images. The two bands are selected to leverage both the sharper spatial resolution of F200W images (PSF $\sim 0 \frown 08$ corresponding to $\sim 0.6-0.7 \mathrm{kpc}$ at $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$ ) and the longer rest-frame wavelength traced by F444W $\left(\lambda_{\text {rest }} \gtrsim 1 \mu \mathrm{~m}\right.$ out to $z \sim 3.5$ ).
Our main findings are described below:

1. For bars with projected semi-major axis $a_{\text {bar }}>1.5$ kpc ( $\sim 2 \times$ the PSF in the F200W images), the bar fraction at $z \sim 2-4$ is low ( $<10 \%$ ), and they appear to be emerging at least as early as $z \sim 4$ when the Universe was $\sim 11 \%$ of its present age. The very existence of bars at these early epochs challenges and constrains many theoretical models of disk and bar evolution. Disk galaxies at those epochs may be significantly different from presentday disks in terms of their gas fraction, turbulence, and the extent to which they are dynamically cold, and it is notable that bars can form in them.
2. Our observed bar fraction is consistent with the bar fraction from $z \sim 0.5-4$ predicted by TNG50 simulations for bars with a semi-major axis $a_{\text {bar }}$ $>1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$. However, TNG50 simulations predict a large population of small bars with $a_{\text {bar }}<1.5$ kpc that our data cannot robustly detect. If such a population of small bars exists, the true bar fraction at $z \sim 2-4$ may be significantly higher than our results. Our observed bar fraction is also broadly consistent with the bar fraction from $z \sim$

$0.5-1.5$ predicted by the Auriga simulations using a sample of 39 Milky-Way-mass halos.
3. Bars can form through spontaneous $m=2$ instabilities in isolated galaxies or be induced via tidal interactions. We present preliminary results suggesting that at $z \geq 1.5$, our sample of barred galaxies shows a larger frequency of nearby neighbors or/and signs of tidal interactions than a control sample of unbarred galaxies. These preliminary results raise the tantalizing possibility that at early epochs ( $z \geq 1.5$ ), bars may preferentially form via tidal interaction. However, future detailed work will be needed to confirm this important result.
4. As cosmic time progresses from $z \sim 4$ to $z \sim 0.5$, we see a rise in bar abundance, bar length, and bar strength. The average projected bar length increases from $\sim 1.7-2.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ at $z \sim 2.5$ to $\sim 2.6-$ 3.8 kpc at $z \sim 0.75$ and the tail of strong bars with high $e_{\text {bar }} \sim 0.6$ to 0.8 becomes more prominent at later times, showing the growth of bars over time.
5. Bars are important in shaping the secular evolution of disk galaxies. As the bar fraction appears to rise from $z \sim 4$ to today, we conclude that bar-driven secular evolution will become progressively more important for driving galaxy evolution towards the present day. At earlier times, when the Universe was less than 4 billion years old
$(z \gtrsim 2)$, alternative mechanisms, such as gas accretion galaxy mergers and tidal interactions, likely played a dominant role in the growth and morphological transformation of galaxies.

# C. COMPARISON WITH HST-BASED STUDIES 

In § 4.1.3 and Figure 7, we noted that at $z \sim 0.5-1.5$ where both $H S T$ and $J W S T$ results exist, the $J W S T$-based observed bar fraction is up to two times higher than that from most HST studies. We suggested in $\S 4.1 .3$ that this difference likely arises because the higher spatial resolution and longer rest-frame NIR wavelengths of $J W S T$ NIRCam images can unveil a population of bars that were previously missed in HST data. In this Appendix, we further substantiate this suggestion through several tests.
We can robustly Identify bars with size $a_{\text {bar }}>2$ times the PSF FWHM (see $\S 3.2 .1$ for details) during ellipse fits. This translates to bars with a size $a_{\text {bar }} \gtrsim 1.5 \mathrm{kpc}$ when using $J W S T$ F200W images (PSF FWHM $\sim 0 \farcs 08$, corresponding to $\sim 0.6-0.7 \mathrm{kpc}$ across $z \sim 0.5-1$ ) and bars with size $a_{\text {bar }} \gtrsim 2.2 \mathrm{kpc}$ with HST WFC3 F160W images (PSF $\sim 0 \farcs 13$, corresponding to $\sim 1-1.2 \mathrm{kpc}$ across $z \sim 0.5-1.5$ ). In the upper right panel of Figure 16, we remove bars with $a_{\text {bar }} \leq 2.2$ kpc that would be robustly identified with JWST F200W images, but not with HST WFC3 images. This leads to the removal of 16 bars in the redshift bin $z \sim 0.5-1$, and lowers the overall $J W S T$ bar fraction based on ellipse fits from $\sim 28 \%$ to $\sim 18 \%$, which is closer to the HST bar fraction of $\sim 7-18 \%$.

Another advantage of JWST images over HST WFC3 images is that they can more effectively identify dust-obscured bars due to their longer wavelength. JWST F444W images trace longer rest-frame wavelength $\left(\lambda_{\text {rest }} \gtrsim 1 \mu m\right)$ than HST ACS or WFC3 images and can more effectively reveal dust-obscured bars. These obscured bars tend to preferentially be weak bars for the following reasons. A strong bar is less likely to be obscured by dust and recent SF because the large gas inflows and strong shear along the bar suppress the accumulation of gas and dust and the triggering of SF along the bar (e.g., Jogee et al. 2005; James et al. 2009; Díaz-García et al. 2020). Conversely, weak bars are more prone to have gas, dust, and SF along the bar and to be obscured by dust. To explore this effect, we remove bars with $e_{\text {bar }} \leq 0.4$ measured in F444W images from the JWST bar fraction. This leads to the removal of 11 bars and lowers the overall JWST bar fraction from $\sim 28 \%$ to $\sim 21 \%$, which is closer to the HST bar fraction of $\sim 7-18 \%$ (lower left panel of Figure 16)

To assess the combined impact of JWST data being able to more robustly identify shorter and weaker bars than HST data, we removed both bars ( $\leq 2.2 \mathrm{kpc}$ ) and weak bars ( $e_{\text {bar }} \leq 0.4$ ) from the JWST bar fraction (see lower right panel of Figure 16). This lowers the overall JWST bar fraction at $z \sim 0.5-1$ from $\sim 28 \%$ to $\sim 10 \%$, which is consistent with most of the HST results. The higher bar fraction measured in our study at $z \sim 0.5-1$ highlight the power of JWST NIRCam images.

abstract:
We present the first estimate of the observed fraction and properties of bars
out to $ z\sim4$ using $\textit{JWST}$ CEERS NIRCam images. We analyze 1770
galaxies with $M_\star > 10^{10} M_\odot$ at $0.5 \leq z \leq 4$ and identify
barred galaxies from 839 moderately inclined disk galaxies via ellipse fits and
visual classification of both F200W and F444W images. Our results apply mainly
to bars with projected semi-major axis $a_{\rm bar}$ $> 1.5 $ kpc ($\sim$ 2
$\times$ PSF in F200W images) that can be robustly traced by ellipse fits. For
such bars, the observed bar fraction at $z\sim$ 2-4 is low ($\lesssim 10\%$),
and they appear to be emerging at least as early as $z\sim 4$. Our observed bar
fraction is consistent with the bar fraction predicted by TNG50 simulations for
large bars with $a_{\rm bar}$ $> 1.5$ kpc at $z \sim$ 0.5-4 and with the bar
fraction from Auriga simulations out to $z \sim$ 1.5. However, TNG50
simulations predict a large population of smaller bars that our data cannot
robustly detect. If such bars exist, the true bar fraction at $z \sim$ 2-4 may
be significantly higher than our results. At $z \ge 1.5$, many barred galaxies
show nearby neighbors, suggesting bars may be tidally triggered. From $z \sim$
4-0.5, the observed bar fraction, average projected bar length, and projected
bar strength rise. Our results highlight the early emergence and evolution of
barred galaxies and the rising importance of bar-driven secular evolution from
$z \sim$4 to today.
